Below is a **complete, self‑contained binding** that lets OCaml code walk a libpcapng frame iterator and run an OCaml callback for every frame.  
It consists of

* `pcapng.mli` – the public OCaml interface  
* `pcapng_stubs.c` – the C‑/C++‑glue (compiled as C++)

You can drop the two files into a small OCaml “library” project, add the stub to your `jbuild`/`dune` file, and you’ll have a nice, idiomatic OCaml API.

---

## 1.  OCaml interface – **`pcapng.mli`**

```ocaml
(* ---------------------------------------------------------------------- *)
(*  libpcapng OCaml bindings                                               *)
(*  Author: <your‑name>                                                   *)
(*  License: MIT (or whatever you prefer)                                 *)
(* ---------------------------------------------------------------------- *)

(** {1 Types} *)

type iterator   (** opaque handle to the underlying C++ iterator *)

type frame = {
  timestamp : int64;   (** nanoseconds since the Unix epoch *)
  data      : bytes;   (** raw packet bytes (copied from the C++ side) *)
  length    : int;     (** length of [data] – kept for convenience *)
}
(** A single captured frame.  The fields are immutable – the record can be
    safely shared between OCaml threads. *)

(** {1 Construction / destruction} *)

val open_file : string -> iterator
(** Open a pcapng file and create an iterator.  Raises [Invalid_argument] if
    the file cannot be opened or the format is wrong. *)

val close : iterator -> unit
(** Explicitly release the underlying C++ object.  After calling this the
    iterator must not be used again.  The finaliser will also close the
    iterator when it is garbage‑collected, so calling [close] is optional. *)

(** {1 Manual iteration} *)

val next : iterator -> frame option
(** Return the next frame, or [None] when the iterator is exhausted.
    The returned [frame] is a fresh OCaml value – the underlying C++ frame
    data is copied. *)

(** {1 Higher‑order iteration} *)

val iter : (frame -> unit) -> iterator -> unit
(** Apply the supplied function to every remaining frame.  The callback is
    invoked in the same thread that calls [iter]; any exception raised by
    the callback aborts the walk and propagates to the caller. *)

(** {1 Convenience} *)

val with_file : string -> (iterator -> 'a) -> 'a
(** [with_file fname f] opens [fname], runs [f it] and finally closes the
    iterator, even if [f] raises.  This is the usual “resource‑bracket”
    pattern in OCaml. *)
```

The interface is deliberately tiny: users only need the abstract type
`iterator`, the immutable record `frame`, and three primitive operations
(`open_file`, `next`, `iter`).  The `with_file` helper is pure OCaml and
does not need any stub support.

---

## 2.  C / C++ glue – **`pcapng_stubs.c`**

> **Important:** The file *must be compiled as C++* (e.g. `g++ -c
> pcapng_stubs.c -I$(ocamlc -where) …`).  The `extern "C"` wrappers expose a
> C ABI that the OCaml runtime can call, while the implementation can use
> the real C++ libpcapng classes.

```c
/* ---------------------------------------------------------------------- */
/*  libpcapng OCaml bindings – C++ stubs                                   */
/*  Author: <your‑name>                                                   */
/*  License: MIT                                                          */
/* ---------------------------------------------------------------------- */

#define CAML_NAME_SPACE
#include <caml/mlvalues.h>
#include <caml/memory.h>
#include <caml/alloc.h>
#include <caml/callback.h>
#include <caml/custom.h>
#include <caml/fail.h>
#include <caml/bigarray.h>
#include <caml/threads.h>

#include <string>
#include <cstdint>
#include <cstring>   // memcpy
#include <exception>

/* ---------------------------------------------------------------------- */
/*  The (fictional) libpcapng C++ API we are binding to                     */
/* ---------------------------------------------------------------------- */
namespace libpcapng {

struct Frame {
    uint64_t timestamp;      // nanoseconds since epoch
    const uint8_t* data;     // pointer owned by the iterator
    size_t length;           // length of the data buffer
};

class FrameIterator {
public:
    explicit FrameIterator(const std::string& filename);
    ~FrameIterator();

    bool has_next() const;
    Frame next();            // advances iterator; undefined if !has_next()
};

/* ---------------------------------------------------------------------- */
/*  Minimal mock implementation – replace with the real library!           */
/* ---------------------------------------------------------------------- */
#include <fstream>
#include <vector>

class FrameIterator {
    std::ifstream in_;
    std::vector<uint8_t> buffer_;
    uint64_t ts_;
    bool eof_;
public:
    explicit FrameIterator(const std::string& fn) : in_(fn, std::ios::binary), eof_(false) {
        if (!in_) throw std::runtime_error("cannot open file");
        // pretend each frame is a 64‑byte blob with a fake timestamp
        ts_ = 0;
    }
    ~FrameIterator() {}
    bool has_next() const { return !eof_; }
    Frame next() {
        if (eof_) throw std::runtime_error("no more frames");
        buffer_.assign(64, 0);
        in_.read(reinterpret_cast<char*>(buffer_.data()), 64);
        std::streamsize got = in_.gcount();
        if (got == 0) { eof_ = true; throw std::runtime_error("no more frames"); }
        if (static_cast<size_t>(got) < 64) buffer_.resize(got);
        Frame f{ ts_, buffer_.data(), buffer_.size() };
        ts_ += 1000000;   // 1 ms per frame – just for demo
        if (in_.eof()) eof_ = true;
        return f;
    }
};

} // namespace libpcapng
/* ---------------------------------------------------------------------- */

using namespace libpcapng;

/* ---------------------------------------------------------------------- */
/*  OCaml custom block that holds a pointer to FrameIterator                */
/* ---------------------------------------------------------------------- */

typedef struct {
    FrameIterator *it;
} iterator_wrap;

/* Finaliser – called when the OCaml value is GC‑collected */
static void iterator_finalize(value v) {
    iterator_wrap *wrap = (iterator_wrap *)Data_custom_val(v);
    if (wrap->it) {
        delete wrap->it;
        wrap->it = nullptr;
    }
}

/* No comparison / hashing needed – we expose only as an opaque handle */
static int iterator_compare(value v1, value v2) {
    iterator_wrap *a = (iterator_wrap *)Data_custom_val(v1);
    iterator_wrap *b = (iterator_wrap *)Data_custom_val(v2);
    return (a->it < b->it) ? -1 : (a->it > b->it);
}
static intnat iterator_hash(value v) {
    iterator_wrap *wrap = (iterator_wrap *)Data_custom_val(v);
    return (intnat)wrap->it;
}

/* Custom operations descriptor */
static struct custom_operations iterator_ops = {
    "pcapng.iterator",
    iterator_finalize,
    iterator_compare,
    iterator_hash,
    custom_serialize_default,
    custom_deserialize_default,
    custom_compare_ext_default,
    custom_fixed_length_default
};

/* ---------------------------------------------------------------------- */
/*  Helper: allocate an OCaml `frame` record from a C++ Frame                */
/* ---------------------------------------------------------------------- */
static value caml_copy_frame(const Frame *f) {
    // OCaml layout: record with 3 fields (timestamp:int64, data:bytes, length:int)
    CAMLparam0();
    CAMLlocal3(ocaml_frame, ocaml_ts, ocaml_data);

    // 1) timestamp – boxed int64
    ocaml_ts = caml_copy_int64((int64_t)f->timestamp);

    // 2) data – copy into a fresh OCaml bytes (string) value
    ocaml_data = caml_alloc_string(f->length);
    memcpy(Bp_val(ocaml_data), f->data, f->length);

    // 3) length – ordinary OCaml int (fits in 31 bits on 32‑bit, 63 bits on 64‑bit)
    value ocaml_len = Val_int(f->length);

    // Build the record
    ocaml_frame = caml_alloc(3, 0);          // tag 0 = normal record
    Store_field(ocaml_frame, 0, ocaml_ts);
    Store_field(ocaml_frame, 1, ocaml_data);
    Store_field(ocaml_frame, 2, ocaml_len);

    CAMLreturn(ocaml_frame);
}

/* ---------------------------------------------------------------------- */
/*  C stub: open_file : string -> iterator                                   */
/* ---------------------------------------------------------------------- */
CAMLprim value caml_pcapng_open_file(value v_path) {
    CAMLparam1(v_path);
    CAMLlocal1(v_wrap);

    const char *c_path = String_val(v_path);
    iterator_wrap *wrap = nullptr;

    // Guard against exceptions from C++ and turn them into OCaml failures
    try {
        FrameIterator *it = new FrameIterator(std::string(c_path));
        wrap = (iterator_wrap *)caml_stat_alloc(sizeof(iterator_wrap));
        wrap->it = it;
    } catch (const std::exception &e) {
        caml_raise_failure(e.what());
    }

    // Wrap the pointer into a custom block
    v_wrap = caml_alloc_custom(&iterator_ops, sizeof(iterator_wrap), 0, 1);
    iterator_wrap *dest = (iterator_wrap *)Data_custom_val(v_wrap);
    *dest = *wrap;                // copy the struct contents
    caml_stat_free(wrap);         // we no longer need the temporary copy

    CAMLreturn(v_wrap);
}

/* ---------------------------------------------------------------------- */
/*  C stub: close : iterator -> unit                                         */
/* ---------------------------------------------------------------------- */
CAMLprim value caml_pcapng_close(value v_it) {
    CAMLparam1(v_it);
    iterator_wrap *wrap = (iterator_wrap *)Data_custom_val(v_it);
    if (wrap->it) {
        delete wrap->it;
        wrap->it = nullptr;
    }
    CAMLreturn(Val_unit);
}

/* ---------------------------------------------------------------------- */
/*  C stub: next : iterator -> frame option                                   */
/* ---------------------------------------------------------------------- */
CAMLprim value caml_pcapng_next(value v_it) {
    CAMLparam1(v_it);
    CAMLlocal1(v_res);
    iterator_wrap *wrap = (iterator_wrap *)Data_custom_val(v_it);

    if (!wrap->it) caml_raise_failure("iterator already closed");

    // Guard against C++ exceptions (e.g. end of stream)
    try {
        if (!wrap->it->has_next()) {
            // None
            v_res = Val_int(0);
        } else {
            Frame f = wrap->it->next();
            value ocaml_f = caml_copy_frame(&f);
            // Some ocaml_f
            v_res = caml_alloc(1, 0);
            Store_field(v_res, 0, ocaml_f);
        }
    } catch (const std::exception &e) {
        caml_raise_failure(e.what());
    }

    CAMLreturn(v_res);
}

/* ---------------------------------------------------------------------- */
/*  C stub: iter : (frame -> unit) -> iterator -> unit                       */
/* ---------------------------------------------------------------------- */
CAMLprim value caml_pcapng_iter(value v_cb, value v_it) {
    CAMLparam2(v_cb, v_it);
    CAMLlocal1(v_cb_res);
    iterator_wrap *wrap = (iterator_wrap *)Data_custom_val(v_it);

    if (!wrap->it) caml_raise_failure("iterator already closed");

    /* Because a callback may allocate, we must release the OCaml lock
       before calling into C++ and reacquire it afterwards. */
    caml_release_runtime_system();

    try {
        while (wrap->it->has_next()) {
            Frame f = wrap->it->next();
            value ocaml_f = caml_copy_frame(&f);

            caml_acquire_runtime_system();   // reacquire before invoking OCaml
            v_cb_res = caml_callback_exn(v_cb, ocaml_f);
            caml_release_runtime_system();   // release again for the next loop

            if (Is_exception_result(v_cb_res)) {
                /* Propagate the OCaml exception */
                caml_acquire_runtime_system();
                caml_raise(v_cb_res);
            }
        }
    } catch (const std::exception &e) {
        caml_acquire_runtime_system();
        caml_raise_failure(e.what());
    }

    caml_acquire_runtime_system();   // make sure we are back in OCaml land
    CAMLreturn(Val_unit);
}

/* ---------------------------------------------------------------------- */
/*  Optional helper that can be written in OCaml (but we expose it here   */
/*  for completeness).  This is *not* a C stub – just a thin wrapper.      */
/* ---------------------------------------------------------------------- */

/* The following OCaml code can be added to the .ml file if you like:

   let with_file fname f =
     let it = open_file fname in
     try
       let r = f it in
       close it; r
     with exn ->
       close it; raise exn
*/

```

---

## 3.  How to compile & link

Assuming the directory structure:

```
pcapng/
│─ pcapng.mli
│─ pcapng.ml          (just the optional `with_file` helper)
│─ pcapng_stubs.c
│─ dune               (or jbuild)
│─ <any other source files>
```

**`dune` example** (for a library named `pcapng`):

```lisp
(library
 (name pcapng)
 (public_name pcapng)
 (modules pcapng)
 (foreign_stubs
  (language cxx)               ; compile the stub as C++
  (names pcapng_stubs)))
```

If you are not using Dune, the equivalent `ocamlc` / `ocamlopt` command line
is roughly:

```sh
# Compile the stub as C++
g++ -c -I$(ocamlc -where) -Wall -Wextra -O2 pcapng_stubs.c -o pcapng_stubs.o

# Build the OCaml library (static for simplicity)
ocamlc -a -o libpcapng.cma pcapng.mli pcapng.ml pcapng_stubs.o
```

Make sure the real libpcapng library (e.g. `-lpcapng`) is linked when you build an
executable that uses the binding.

---

## 4.  Example usage (OCaml)

```ocaml
open Pcapng

let print_frame f =
  Printf.printf "frame %Ld bytes @ %Ld ns\n%!"
    (Int64.of_int f.length) f.timestamp

let () =
  with_file "sample.pcapng" (fun it ->
      (* Manual iteration *)
      match next it with
      | None -> print_endline "empty file"
      | Some first ->
          print_frame first;
          (* Higher‑order iteration for the rest *)
          iter print_frame it
    )
```

Running the program will print a line for every frame in `sample.pcapng`.

---

### What the binding provides

| Feature | How it works |
|---------|--------------|
| **Opaque iterator** | Stored in a custom block with a finaliser (`iterator_wrap`). |
| **Automatic resource cleanup** | Finaliser runs on GC; `close` can be called explicitly. |
| **Manual `next`** | Returns an `option` value; no allocation if the iterator is exhausted. |
| **Higher‑order `iter`** | Calls the user‑provided OCaml function for each frame; propagates exceptions. |
| **Thread‑safety** | The stub releases the OCaml runtime lock while walking the C++ iterator, allowing other OCaml threads to run. |
| **Zero‑copy on the OCaml side** | The frame data is *copied* into an OCaml `bytes` value (the C++ library owns its own buffer). If you need zero‑copy you could expose a `bigarray` backed by the C++ buffer, but that requires extra lifetime management. |
| **Error handling** | All C++ exceptions are caught and turned into `Failure` (or more specific OCaml exceptions if you wish). |

That’s it! Drop the two files into your project, compile the stub as C++, and you have a clean, idiomatic OCaml API that lets users write:

```ocaml
Pcapng.iter (fun f -> …) it
```

or use `next` manually – whichever style fits their code. Happy hacking!
